+## Syntax-First Worker Prompt Rule
+
+When the recent failures show the same syntax error shape repeating, the worker prompt should explicitly ask for one syntactically valid replacement file and no other files. The prompt should prefer already-valid helper patterns from the existing test file instead of asking the worker to invent new control flow.
+
+For Python mutation-test recovery, the worker should:
+
+- load the committed fixture first
+- assert the committed fixture is valid before mutating it
+- add exactly one mutation case for the selected checkbox
+- use `copy.deepcopy` for fixture mutation when needed
+- use `with self.assertRaises(AssertionError):` for expected validation failure
+- avoid generated pseudo-code, abbreviated comparisons, and prose-like conditionals
+
+## Preflight Failure Classification Rule
+
+Treat syntax and compile failures as preflight-quality failures even when they are discovered during the validation command set. After two such failures for the same task, do not broaden scope. The next cycle should reduce file count, reduce edited line count, and remove all nonessential context from the worker request.
+
+Known syntax/compile markers include:
+
+- `SyntaxError`
+- `py_compile`
+- `TS1005`
+- `TS1109`
+- `TS1128`
+- `Failed to import test module` when the import failed because the changed file did not parse
 
